{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_014xktZyj7BuQ7PFCXD8u3Q5","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# Workflows\n     2→\n     3→Cloche workflows define a directed graph of steps connected by named results.\n     4→\n     5→## Workflow Locations\n     6→\n     7→Cloche distinguishes two workflow locations based on the file they live in:\n     8→\n     9→**Container workflows** (`.cloche/*.cloche` except `host.cloche`) — Run inside a Docker\n    10→container via `cloche-agent`. Steps may only be `agent` or `script` type. These are the\n    11→standard workflows for coding tasks.\n    12→\n    13→**Host workflows** (`.cloche/host.cloche`) — Run on the host machine as the daemon\n    14→process. Steps may be `agent`, `script`, or `workflow` type. The `workflow` step type\n    15→dispatches a container workflow run and waits for it to complete. This is the extension\n    16→point for custom orchestration strategies.\n    17→\n    18→A single `host.cloche` file may contain **multiple named workflows**. The daemon\n    19→uses up to three workflow phases for orchestration:\n    20→\n    21→| Phase | Workflow name | Purpose |\n    22→|-------|--------------|---------|\n    23→| 1 | `list-tasks` | Discover available work. Output is JSONL (one task per line). |\n    24→| 2 | `main` | Do the work. Receives a task ID via `CLOCHE_TASK_ID` env var. |\n    25→| 3 | `finalize` | Post-main cleanup. Runs on **both** success and failure. |\n    26→\n    27→Only `main` is required. If `list-tasks` is absent, the daemon uses a legacy\n    28→single-function mode. If `finalize` is absent, it is skipped.\n    29→\n    30→The `list-tasks` workflow's final step output is parsed as JSONL. Each line is a JSON\n    31→object with the following fields:\n    32→\n    33→| Field | Required | Description |\n    34→|-------|----------|-------------|\n    35→| `id` | yes | Unique task identifier |\n    36→| `status` | yes | One of `open`, `closed`, `in-progress` |\n    37→| `title` | no | Short summary |\n    38→| `description` | no | Full description |\n    39→| `metadata` | no | Arbitrary key-value pairs |\n    40→\n    41→The daemon picks the first task with status `open` (or empty, for backward\n    42→compatibility), runs `main` with that task ID, then runs `finalize` with the outcome.\n    43→Tasks are deduplicated within a configurable timeout window to prevent rapid\n    44→reassignment.\n    45→\n    46→The convention is enforced at parse time: a `workflow_name` step in a container workflow\n    47→file is a parse error.\n    48→\n    49→## Concepts\n    50→\n    51→| Concept  | Description                                                        |\n    52→|----------|--------------------------------------------------------------------|\n    53→| workflow | A named graph of steps connected by result wiring                  |\n    54→| step     | A unit of work (inferred: `prompt` = agent, `run` = script)        |\n    55→| result   | A named outcome reported by a step (e.g. \"success\", \"fail\")       |\n    56→| wiring   | Maps a step's result to the next step, with optional output mappings |\n    57→| done     | Built-in terminal step — successful completion                     |\n    58→| abort    | Built-in terminal step — failure with error reporting              |\n    59→\n    60→## Step Types\n    61→\n    62→Step type is inferred from the fields present in the step body:\n    63→\n    64→**agent** (has `prompt`) — Invokes a coding agent (Claude Code, or any tool conforming\n    65→to the agent adapter interface) with a prompt. The agent works autonomously inside the\n    66→container. Available in both host and container workflows.\n    67→\n    68→**script** (has `run`) — Runs a shell command. Used for tests, linters, validators, or\n    69→any deterministic check. Available in both host and container workflows.\n    70→\n    71→**workflow** (has `workflow_name`) — Dispatches a named container workflow run and blocks\n    72→until it completes. Only available in host workflows (`host.cloche`).\n    73→\n    74→A step with more than one of `prompt`, `run`, or `workflow_name`, or none of them, is a\n    75→parse error.\n    76→\n    77→## DSL Syntax\n    78→\n    79→```\n    80→workflow \"develop\" {\n    81→  container {\n    82→    image = \"my-project:latest\"\n    83→    agent_command = \"claude\"\n    84→  }\n    85→\n    86→  step implement {\n    87→    prompt = file(\".cloche/prompts/implement.md\")\n    88→    results = [success, fail]\n    89→  }\n    90→\n    91→  step test {\n    92→    run = \"make test && make lint\"\n    93→    results = [success, fail]\n    94→  }\n    95→\n    96→  step fix {\n    97→    prompt = file(\".cloche/prompts/fix.md\")\n    98→    max_attempts = \"3\"\n    99→    results = [success, fail, give-up]\n   100→  }\n   101→\n   102→  // Wiring: step:result -> next_step [optional output mappings]\n   103→  implement:success -> test\n   104→  implement:fail    -> abort\n   105→  test:success      -> done\n   106→  test:fail         -> fix\n   107→  fix:success       -> test\n   108→  fix:fail          -> abort\n   109→  fix:give-up       -> abort\n   110→}\n   111→```\n   112→\n   113→## Key Properties\n   114→\n   115→**Step type is inferred from content.** A `prompt` field makes it an agent step; a `run`\n   116→field makes it a script step.\n   117→\n   118→**Steps declare their possible results.** A step decides at runtime which result to\n   119→report. The graph engine follows the wiring to determine the next step.\n   120→\n   121→**Wiring is separate from step definitions.** This enables inserting new steps between\n   122→existing ones by rewiring — without modifying either step. This is the foundation for\n   123→Cloche's self-evolution feature.\n   124→\n   125→**Graphs are validated at parse time.** The parser checks that all declared results are\n   126→wired, no steps are orphaned, and an entry point exists.\n   127→\n   128→## Wire Output Mappings\n   129→\n   130→Wires can include output mappings that extract values from a step's output and inject\n   131→them as environment variables into the target step:\n   132→\n   133→```\n   134→step-a:success -> step-b [ ENV_VAR = output.field, OTHER = output.list[0].name ]\n   135→```\n   136→\n   137→The general form:\n   138→\n   139→```\n   140→FROM:RESULT -> TO [ KEY = EXPR, KEY = EXPR, ... ]\n   141→```\n   142→\n   143→Where `KEY` is the environment variable name and `EXPR` is an output path expression\n   144→starting with the contextual keyword `output`:\n   145→\n   146→| Expression | Meaning |\n   147→|---|---|\n   148→| `output` | Raw output (full string) |\n   149→| `output.key` | JSON object field access |\n   150→| `output[N]` | JSON array index (0-based) |\n   151→| `output.a.b.c` | Deeply nested field access |\n   152→| `output.items[0].name` | Mixed field and index chaining |\n   153→\n   154→If the source step's output is valid JSON, path expressions navigate the parsed\n   155→structure. If the output is plain text, only bare `output` is valid. The resolved\n   156→value is converted to a string for env var injection.\n   157→\n   158→If two wires targeting the same step both map the same env var key, validation\n   159→returns an error (the mapping would be ambiguous). The same key may be used on\n   160→wires to different steps without conflict.\n   161→\n   162→## Workflow-Level Configuration Blocks\n   163→\n   164→Workflows support a configuration block at the workflow level to set defaults for all\n   165→steps. The block name depends on the workflow location:\n   166→\n   167→**`container {}`** — For container workflows. Sets container image, agent command, and\n   168→network allowlist.\n   169→\n   170→```\n   171→workflow \"develop\" {\n   172→  container {\n   173→    image = \"my-project:latest\"\n   174→    agent_command = \"claude\"\n   175→    agent_args = \"-p --dangerously-skip-permissions\"\n   176→  }\n   177→  ...\n   178→}\n   179→```\n   180→\n   181→Supported keys: `image`, `agent_command`, `agent_args`, `network_allow`.\n   182→\n   183→**`host {}`** — For host workflows (`host.cloche`). Sets agent defaults for agent steps\n   184→running on the host machine.\n   185→\n   186→```\n   187→workflow \"main\" {\n   188→  host {\n   189→    agent_command = \"claude\"\n   190→  }\n   191→  ...\n   192→}\n   193→```\n   194→\n   195→Supported keys: `agent_command`, `agent_args`.\n   196→\n   197→Step-level `agent_command` and `agent_args` override workflow-level defaults. The\n   198→resolution order is: step-level > workflow-level block > `CLOCHE_AGENT_COMMAND` env\n   199→var > default `claude`.\n   200→\n   201→## Host Workflow Example\n   202→\n   203→A three-phase `host.cloche` with separate `list-tasks`, `main`, and `finalize`\n   204→workflows:\n   205→\n   206→```\n   207→# .cloche/host.cloche — runs on the host machine\n   208→\n   209→workflow \"list-tasks\" {\n   210→  step fetch-tickets {\n   211→    run     = \"bash .cloche/scripts/ready-tasks.sh\"\n   212→    results = [success, fail]\n   213→  }\n   214→\n   215→  fetch-tickets:success -> done\n   216→  fetch-tickets:fail    -> abort\n   217→}\n   218→\n   219→workflow \"main\" {\n   220→  host {\n   221→    agent_command = \"claude\"\n   222→  }\n   223→\n   224→  step prepare-prompt {\n   225→    run     = \"bash .cloche/scripts/prepare-prompt.sh\"\n   226→    results = [success, fail]\n   227→  }\n   228→\n   229→  step develop {\n   230→    workflow_name = \"develop\"\n   231→    results       = [success, fail]\n   232→  }\n   233→\n   234→  prepare-prompt:success -> develop\n   235→  prepare-prompt:fail    -> abort\n   236→  develop:success        -> done\n   237→  develop:fail           -> done\n   238→}\n   239→\n   240→workflow \"finalize\" {\n   241→  step push-for-review {\n   242→    run     = \"bash .cloche/scripts/push-for-review.sh\"\n   243→    results = [success, fail]\n   244→  }\n   245→\n   246→  push-for-review:success -> done\n   247→  push-for-review:fail    -> done\n   248→}\n   249→```\n   250→\n   251→The daemon runs `list-tasks` to discover work (output is JSONL), picks an open task,\n   252→runs `main` with `CLOCHE_TASK_ID` set, then runs `finalize` regardless of outcome.\n   253→The `list-tasks` script writes one JSON object per line to `$CLOCHE_STEP_OUTPUT`.\n   254→The `main` workflow receives the task ID and is responsible for claiming the ticket.\n   255→The `finalize` workflow decides what to do based on the outcome (available via\n   256→`CLOCHE_MAIN_OUTCOME` and `CLOCHE_MAIN_RUN_ID` env vars).\n   257→\n   258→## Execution Model\n   259→\n   260→**Container workflows** are parsed and executed by `cloche-agent` inside a Docker\n   261→container. The agent walks the graph: execute current step, read its result, follow the\n   262→wiring to the next step. This continues until a terminal (`done` or `abort`) is reached.\n   263→All steps run inside the same container. File state accumulates naturally across steps.\n   264→\n   265→**Host workflows** are parsed and executed by the daemon on the host machine. A single\n   266→`host.cloche` file may contain multiple named workflows; the daemon orchestrates them\n   267→in three phases (list-tasks → main → finalize). Script steps run via `sh -c` with the\n   268→working directory set to the **main git worktree** (i.e. the main branch checkout), even\n   269→if the project directory is a linked worktree on a different branch. This ensures\n   270→host-workflow scripts from main are used for all runs. Workflow steps dispatch container\n   271→runs via the daemon's standard run pipeline. Environment variables (`CLOCHE_TASK_ID`,\n   272→`CLOCHE_PROJECT_DIR`, etc.) are injected into each step; `CLOCHE_PROJECT_DIR` still\n   273→points to the actual project directory.\n   274→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"0a1eb545-c5fc-4d99-8df4-f479f783e58f","uuid":"ab6ec1c2-5af2-4a76-b046-ce1d3cca5f73","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/workspace/docs/workflows.md","content":"# Workflows\n\nCloche workflows define a directed graph of steps connected by named results.\n\n## Workflow Locations\n\nCloche distinguishes two workflow locations based on the file they live in:\n\n**Container workflows** (`.cloche/*.cloche` except `host.cloche`) — Run inside a Docker\ncontainer via `cloche-agent`. Steps may only be `agent` or `script` type. These are the\nstandard workflows for coding tasks.\n\n**Host workflows** (`.cloche/host.cloche`) — Run on the host machine as the daemon\nprocess. Steps may be `agent`, `script`, or `workflow` type. The `workflow` step type\ndispatches a container workflow run and waits for it to complete. This is the extension\npoint for custom orchestration strategies.\n\nA single `host.cloche` file may contain **multiple named workflows**. The daemon\nuses up to three workflow phases for orchestration:\n\n| Phase | Workflow name | Purpose |\n|-------|--------------|---------|\n| 1 | `list-tasks` | Discover available work. Output is JSONL (one task per line). |\n| 2 | `main` | Do the work. Receives a task ID via `CLOCHE_TASK_ID` env var. |\n| 3 | `finalize` | Post-main cleanup. Runs on **both** success and failure. |\n\nOnly `main` is required. If `list-tasks` is absent, the daemon uses a legacy\nsingle-function mode. If `finalize` is absent, it is skipped.\n\nThe `list-tasks` workflow's final step output is parsed as JSONL. Each line is a JSON\nobject with the following fields:\n\n| Field | Required | Description |\n|-------|----------|-------------|\n| `id` | yes | Unique task identifier |\n| `status` | yes | One of `open`, `closed`, `in-progress` |\n| `title` | no | Short summary |\n| `description` | no | Full description |\n| `metadata` | no | Arbitrary key-value pairs |\n\nThe daemon picks the first task with status `open` (or empty, for backward\ncompatibility), runs `main` with that task ID, then runs `finalize` with the outcome.\nTasks are deduplicated within a configurable timeout window to prevent rapid\nreassignment.\n\nThe convention is enforced at parse time: a `workflow_name` step in a container workflow\nfile is a parse error.\n\n## Concepts\n\n| Concept  | Description                                                        |\n|----------|--------------------------------------------------------------------|\n| workflow | A named graph of steps connected by result wiring                  |\n| step     | A unit of work (inferred: `prompt` = agent, `run` = script)        |\n| result   | A named outcome reported by a step (e.g. \"success\", \"fail\")       |\n| wiring   | Maps a step's result to the next step, with optional output mappings |\n| done     | Built-in terminal step — successful completion                     |\n| abort    | Built-in terminal step — failure with error reporting              |\n\n## Step Types\n\nStep type is inferred from the fields present in the step body:\n\n**agent** (has `prompt`) — Invokes a coding agent (Claude Code, or any tool conforming\nto the agent adapter interface) with a prompt. The agent works autonomously inside the\ncontainer. Available in both host and container workflows.\n\n**script** (has `run`) — Runs a shell command. Used for tests, linters, validators, or\nany deterministic check. Available in both host and container workflows.\n\n**workflow** (has `workflow_name`) — Dispatches a named container workflow run and blocks\nuntil it completes. Only available in host workflows (`host.cloche`).\n\nA step with more than one of `prompt`, `run`, or `workflow_name`, or none of them, is a\nparse error.\n\n## DSL Syntax\n\n```\nworkflow \"develop\" {\n  container {\n    image = \"my-project:latest\"\n    agent_command = \"claude\"\n  }\n\n  step implement {\n    prompt = file(\".cloche/prompts/implement.md\")\n    results = [success, fail]\n  }\n\n  step test {\n    run = \"make test && make lint\"\n    results = [success, fail]\n  }\n\n  step fix {\n    prompt = file(\".cloche/prompts/fix.md\")\n    max_attempts = \"3\"\n    results = [success, fail, give-up]\n  }\n\n  // Wiring: step:result -> next_step [optional output mappings]\n  implement:success -> test\n  implement:fail    -> abort\n  test:success      -> done\n  test:fail         -> fix\n  fix:success       -> test\n  fix:fail          -> abort\n  fix:give-up       -> abort\n}\n```\n\n## Key Properties\n\n**Step type is inferred from content.** A `prompt` field makes it an agent step; a `run`\nfield makes it a script step.\n\n**Steps declare their possible results.** A step decides at runtime which result to\nreport. The graph engine follows the wiring to determine the next step.\n\n**Wiring is separate from step definitions.** This enables inserting new steps between\nexisting ones by rewiring — without modifying either step. This is the foundation for\nCloche's self-evolution feature.\n\n**Graphs are validated at parse time.** The parser checks that all declared results are\nwired, no steps are orphaned, and an entry point exists.\n\n## Wire Output Mappings\n\nWires can include output mappings that extract values from a step's output and inject\nthem as environment variables into the target step:\n\n```\nstep-a:success -> step-b [ ENV_VAR = output.field, OTHER = output.list[0].name ]\n```\n\nThe general form:\n\n```\nFROM:RESULT -> TO [ KEY = EXPR, KEY = EXPR, ... ]\n```\n\nWhere `KEY` is the environment variable name and `EXPR` is an output path expression\nstarting with the contextual keyword `output`:\n\n| Expression | Meaning |\n|---|---|\n| `output` | Raw output (full string) |\n| `output.key` | JSON object field access |\n| `output[N]` | JSON array index (0-based) |\n| `output.a.b.c` | Deeply nested field access |\n| `output.items[0].name` | Mixed field and index chaining |\n\nIf the source step's output is valid JSON, path expressions navigate the parsed\nstructure. If the output is plain text, only bare `output` is valid. The resolved\nvalue is converted to a string for env var injection.\n\nIf two wires targeting the same step both map the same env var key, validation\nreturns an error (the mapping would be ambiguous). The same key may be used on\nwires to different steps without conflict.\n\n## Workflow-Level Configuration Blocks\n\nWorkflows support a configuration block at the workflow level to set defaults for all\nsteps. The block name depends on the workflow location:\n\n**`container {}`** — For container workflows. Sets container image, agent command, and\nnetwork allowlist.\n\n```\nworkflow \"develop\" {\n  container {\n    image = \"my-project:latest\"\n    agent_command = \"claude\"\n    agent_args = \"-p --dangerously-skip-permissions\"\n  }\n  ...\n}\n```\n\nSupported keys: `image`, `agent_command`, `agent_args`, `network_allow`.\n\n**`host {}`** — For host workflows (`host.cloche`). Sets agent defaults for agent steps\nrunning on the host machine.\n\n```\nworkflow \"main\" {\n  host {\n    agent_command = \"claude\"\n  }\n  ...\n}\n```\n\nSupported keys: `agent_command`, `agent_args`.\n\nStep-level `agent_command` and `agent_args` override workflow-level defaults. The\nresolution order is: step-level > workflow-level block > `CLOCHE_AGENT_COMMAND` env\nvar > default `claude`.\n\n## Host Workflow Example\n\nA three-phase `host.cloche` with separate `list-tasks`, `main`, and `finalize`\nworkflows:\n\n```\n# .cloche/host.cloche — runs on the host machine\n\nworkflow \"list-tasks\" {\n  step fetch-tickets {\n    run     = \"bash .cloche/scripts/ready-tasks.sh\"\n    results = [success, fail]\n  }\n\n  fetch-tickets:success -> done\n  fetch-tickets:fail    -> abort\n}\n\nworkflow \"main\" {\n  host {\n    agent_command = \"claude\"\n  }\n\n  step prepare-prompt {\n    run     = \"bash .cloche/scripts/prepare-prompt.sh\"\n    results = [success, fail]\n  }\n\n  step develop {\n    workflow_name = \"develop\"\n    results       = [success, fail]\n  }\n\n  prepare-prompt:success -> develop\n  prepare-prompt:fail    -> abort\n  develop:success        -> done\n  develop:fail           -> done\n}\n\nworkflow \"finalize\" {\n  step push-for-review {\n    run     = \"bash .cloche/scripts/push-for-review.sh\"\n    results = [success, fail]\n  }\n\n  push-for-review:success -> done\n  push-for-review:fail    -> done\n}\n```\n\nThe daemon runs `list-tasks` to discover work (output is JSONL), picks an open task,\nruns `main` with `CLOCHE_TASK_ID` set, then runs `finalize` regardless of outcome.\nThe `list-tasks` script writes one JSON object per line to `$CLOCHE_STEP_OUTPUT`.\nThe `main` workflow receives the task ID and is responsible for claiming the ticket.\nThe `finalize` workflow decides what to do based on the outcome (available via\n`CLOCHE_MAIN_OUTCOME` and `CLOCHE_MAIN_RUN_ID` env vars).\n\n## Execution Model\n\n**Container workflows** are parsed and executed by `cloche-agent` inside a Docker\ncontainer. The agent walks the graph: execute current step, read its result, follow the\nwiring to the next step. This continues until a terminal (`done` or `abort`) is reached.\nAll steps run inside the same container. File state accumulates naturally across steps.\n\n**Host workflows** are parsed and executed by the daemon on the host machine. A single\n`host.cloche` file may contain multiple named workflows; the daemon orchestrates them\nin three phases (list-tasks → main → finalize). Script steps run via `sh -c` with the\nworking directory set to the **main git worktree** (i.e. the main branch checkout), even\nif the project directory is a linked worktree on a different branch. This ensures\nhost-workflow scripts from main are used for all runs. Workflow steps dispatch container\nruns via the daemon's standard run pipeline. Environment variables (`CLOCHE_TASK_ID`,\n`CLOCHE_PROJECT_DIR`, etc.) are injected into each step; `CLOCHE_PROJECT_DIR` still\npoints to the actual project directory.\n","numLines":274,"startLine":1,"totalLines":274}}}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01EWk6EpFXVfnY7VLzXRL35L","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# Cloche Usage\n     2→\n     3→Cloche runs containerized workflows for autonomous coding agents. You define a\n     4→workflow graph in the `.cloche` DSL, Cloche copies your project into a Docker\n     5→container, runs the workflow steps (agent prompts and shell scripts), and extracts\n     6→results to a git branch.\n     7→\n     8→## Core Concepts\n     9→\n    10→- **Workflow**: A directed graph of steps connected by named-result wiring.\n    11→- **Step**: A unit of work. Type is inferred: `prompt` = agent step, `run` = script step, `workflow_name` = workflow step (host only).\n    12→- **Result**: A named outcome reported by a step (e.g. `success`, `fail`, `needs-research`). Steps declare their possible results; the engine follows wiring based on the reported result.\n    13→- **Wiring**: Maps `step:result` pairs to the next step. Separate from step definitions.\n    14→- **Terminals**: `done` (success) and `abort` (failure) are built-in terminal targets.\n    15→\n    16→## Workflow DSL\n    17→\n    18→Workflow files use the `.cloche` extension and live in `.cloche/`. The first step\n    19→declared is the entry point. Graphs are validated at parse time (all results wired,\n    20→no orphans, entry point exists).\n    21→\n    22→### Minimal Example\n    23→\n    24→```\n    25→workflow \"develop\" {\n    26→  step implement {\n    27→    prompt = file(\".cloche/prompts/implement.md\")\n    28→    results = [success, fail]\n    29→  }\n    30→\n    31→  step test {\n    32→    run = \"make test 2>&1\"\n    33→    results = [success, fail]\n    34→  }\n    35→\n    36→  implement:success -> test\n    37→  implement:fail -> abort\n    38→  test:success -> done\n    39→  test:fail -> abort\n    40→}\n    41→```\n    42→\n    43→### Step Configuration\n    44→\n    45→| Key | Type | Description |\n    46→|-----|------|-------------|\n    47→| `prompt` | string or `file(\"path\")` | Prompt template. Makes this an agent step. |\n    48→| `run` | string | Shell command. Makes this a script step. |\n    49→| `workflow_name` | string | Container workflow to dispatch. Makes this a workflow step (host only). |\n    50→| `results` | ident list | Declared result names, e.g. `[success, fail, give-up]`. |\n    51→| `max_attempts` | string | Max retries before automatic `give-up` result, e.g. `\"2\"`. |\n    52→| `timeout` | string | Step timeout as Go duration, e.g. `\"30m\"`, `\"2h\"`. Default: 30m. |\n    53→| `agent_command` | string | Agent binary name(s), comma-separated for fallback chains, e.g. `\"claude,gemini\"`. |\n    54→| `agent_args` | string | Override default agent arguments. |\n    55→| `feedback` | string | Set to `\"true\"` to include `.cloche/output/*.log` content in the prompt. |\n    56→| `prompt_step` | string | For workflow steps: which preceding step's output to use as the prompt. |\n    57→\n    58→A step must have exactly one of `prompt`, `run`, or `workflow_name`.\n    59→\n    60→### The `file()` Function\n    61→\n    62→`file(\"path\")` reads the file at the given path relative to the working directory\n    63→(`/workspace/` in containers) at execution time, not parse time. Use it for prompt\n    64→templates:\n    65→\n    66→```\n    67→prompt = file(\".cloche/prompts/implement.md\")\n    68→```\n    69→\n    70→### The `container {}` Block\n    71→\n    72→Can appear at step level or workflow level. Keys are stored with a `container.` prefix.\n    73→\n    74→**Step level** — per-step container config:\n    75→```\n    76→step code {\n    77→  prompt = file(\".cloche/prompts/implement.md\")\n    78→  container {\n    79→    image         = \"custom-agent:v2\"\n    80→    memory        = \"4g\"\n    81→    network_allow = [\"docs.python.org\", \"api.example.com\"]\n    82→  }\n    83→  results = [success, fail]\n    84→}\n    85→```\n    86→\n    87→**Workflow level** — defaults for all steps:\n    88→```\n    89→workflow \"develop\" {\n    90→  container {\n    91→    agent_command = \"gemini\"\n    92→    image         = \"myregistry/myimage:v2\"\n    93→    memory        = \"4g\"\n    94→  }\n    95→  ...\n    96→}\n    97→```\n    98→\n    99→Supported keys: `image`, `memory`, `network_allow`, `agent_command`, `agent_args`.\n   100→\n   101→### The `host {}` Block\n   102→\n   103→Can appear at workflow level in host workflows (`.cloche/host.cloche`). Keys are stored\n   104→with a `host.` prefix. Configures agent defaults for agent steps running on the host.\n   105→\n   106→```\n   107→workflow \"main\" {\n   108→  host {\n   109→    agent_command = \"claude\"\n   110→  }\n   111→  ...\n   112→}\n   113→```\n   114→\n   115→Supported keys: `agent_command`, `agent_args`. Step-level `agent_command` and\n   116→`agent_args` config keys override the workflow-level `host {}` defaults.\n   117→\n   118→### Wiring Syntax\n   119→\n   120→Connect steps with `step:result -> next_step`:\n   121→\n   122→```\n   123→implement:success -> test\n   124→implement:fail -> abort\n   125→test:success -> done\n   126→test:fail -> fix\n   127→```\n   128→\n   129→### Wire Output Mappings\n   130→\n   131→Extract values from a step's JSON output and inject as env vars into the target:\n   132→\n   133→```\n   134→step-a:success -> step-b [ ENV_VAR = output.field, OTHER = output.list[0].name ]\n   135→```\n   136→\n   137→Path expressions:\n   138→\n   139→| Expression | Meaning |\n   140→|---|---|\n   141→| `output` | Raw output (full string) |\n   142→| `output.key` | JSON object field access |\n   143→| `output[N]` | JSON array index (0-based) |\n   144→| `output.a.b.c` | Deeply nested field access |\n   145→| `output.items[0].name` | Mixed field and index chaining |\n   146→\n   147→If the output is valid JSON, path expressions navigate the structure. If it's plain\n   148→text, only bare `output` works.\n   149→\n   150→### Retry Loops\n   151→\n   152→Wire failures back to earlier steps:\n   153→\n   154→```\n   155→test:fail -> fix\n   156→fix:success -> test    // retry the test\n   157→fix:fail -> abort\n   158→```\n   159→\n   160→Use `max_attempts` to cap retries. When exhausted, the step returns `give-up`:\n   161→\n   162→```\n   163→step fix {\n   164→  prompt = file(\".cloche/prompts/fix.md\")\n   165→  max_attempts = \"2\"\n   166→  results = [success, fail, give-up]\n   167→}\n   168→```\n   169→\n   170→### Parallel Branches (Fanout)\n   171→\n   172→Wire one result to multiple targets for concurrent execution:\n   173→\n   174→```\n   175→test:success -> lint\n   176→test:success -> quality\n   177→```\n   178→\n   179→### Collect (Join)\n   180→\n   181→Synchronize parallel branches:\n   182→\n   183→```\n   184→collect all(lint:success, quality:success) -> done\n   185→collect any(lint:success, quality:success) -> done\n   186→```\n   187→\n   188→`all` fires when every condition is met. `any` fires when at least one is.\n   189→\n   190→### Comments\n   191→\n   192→Line comments with `//`:\n   193→\n   194→```\n   195→// This is a comment\n   196→implement:success -> test  // inline comment\n   197→```\n   198→\n   199→## Result Protocol\n   200→\n   201→Steps report results by printing a marker line to stdout:\n   202→\n   203→```\n   204→CLOCHE_RESULT:<name>\n   205→```\n   206→\n   207→For example: `CLOCHE_RESULT:success`, `CLOCHE_RESULT:needs-research`, `CLOCHE_RESULT:give-up`.\n   208→\n   209→Rules:\n   210→- The **last** `CLOCHE_RESULT:` line wins if multiple are printed.\n   211→- Marker lines are **stripped** from captured output (not passed to logs or downstream steps).\n   212→- The result name must match one of the step's declared `results`.\n   213→- For script steps with no marker: exit 0 = `success`, exit non-zero = `fail`.\n   214→- For agent steps: if exit non-zero with a marker, the marker result is used. If exit non-zero without a marker, falls back to the next agent in the fallback chain (or returns `fail` if last).\n   215→\n   216→## Prompt Assembly\n   217→\n   218→When an agent step runs, Cloche assembles a prompt from these sections (joined by blank lines):\n   219→\n   220→1. **Step template**: The step's `prompt` content (inline string or resolved `file(\"path\")`).\n   221→2. **User request**: Content of `.cloche/<run-id>/prompt.txt` (set via `--prompt` flag), prefixed with `## User Request`.\n   222→3. **Validation output** (opt-in): If `feedback = \"true\"`, reads all `.log` files from `.cloche/output/` and includes them prefixed with `## Validation Output`.\n   223→4. **Result selection**: Lists the step's declared results with instructions to print exactly one `CLOCHE_RESULT:<name>` marker.\n   224→\n   225→The assembled prompt is passed to the agent command via stdin.\n   226→\n   227→## Agent Command Resolution\n   228→\n   229→Priority (highest to lowest):\n   230→1. Step-level `agent_command`\n   231→2. Workflow-level config block (`container { agent_command }` for container workflows, `host { agent_command }` for host workflows)\n   232→3. `CLOCHE_AGENT_COMMAND` environment variable\n   233→4. Default: `claude`\n   234→\n   235→### Fallback Chains\n   236→\n   237→Comma-separated commands are tried in order:\n   238→\n   239→```\n   240→agent_command = \"claude,gemini,codex\"\n   241→```\n   242→\n   243→- **Command not found / failed to start** — try next command\n   244→- **Exit non-zero without `CLOCHE_RESULT` marker** — try next command\n   245→- **Exit non-zero with `CLOCHE_RESULT` marker** — use that result (no fallback)\n   246→- **Exit 0** — use result (no fallback)\n   247→- **All commands fail to start** — step returns an error\n   248→- **Last command crashes without marker** — step returns `fail`\n   249→\n   250→Known agents (e.g. `claude`) get default arguments (`-p --output-format stream-json --verbose --dangerously-skip-permissions`). Unknown agents receive the prompt on stdin with no flags. Override with `agent_args`.\n   251→\n   252→### Agent Setup Guides\n   253→\n   254→For detailed container setup instructions per agent:\n   255→\n   256→- [How to set up Claude Code](agent-setup-claude.md) — session-based auth, no API key needed\n   257→- [How to set up Codex](agent-setup-codex.md) — API key configuration\n   258→\n   259→## Workflow Locations\n   260→\n   261→**Container workflows** (`.cloche/*.cloche` except `host.cloche`) run inside Docker\n   262→via `cloche-agent`. Steps may only be `agent` or `script` type.\n   263→\n   264→**Host workflow** (`.cloche/host.cloche`) runs on the host machine as the daemon.\n   265→Steps may be `agent`, `script`, or `workflow` type. The `workflow_name` step type\n   266→dispatches a container workflow run and blocks until it completes. Script steps\n   267→execute with their working directory set to the main git worktree, so host-workflow\n   268→fixes on main are available to in-flight runs even if they branched earlier.\n   269→\n   270→A single `host.cloche` file may contain **multiple named workflows**. The daemon\n   271→uses up to three workflow phases for orchestration:\n   272→\n   273→| Phase | Workflow name | Purpose |\n   274→|-------|--------------|---------|\n   275→| 1 | `list-tasks` | Discover available work. Output is JSONL (one task per line). |\n   276→| 2 | `main` | Do the work. Receives a task ID via `CLOCHE_TASK_ID` env var. |\n   277→| 3 | `finalize` | Post-main cleanup. Runs on **both** success and failure. |\n   278→\n   279→Only `main` is required. If `list-tasks` is absent, the daemon uses a single-workflow\n   280→mode. If `finalize` is absent, it is skipped.\n   281→\n   282→### list-tasks Output Format\n   283→\n   284→The `list-tasks` workflow's final step output is parsed as JSONL. Each line is a JSON\n   285→object:\n   286→\n   287→| Field | Required | Description |\n   288→|-------|----------|-------------|\n   289→| `id` | yes | Unique task identifier |\n   290→| `status` | yes | One of `open`, `closed`, `in-progress` |\n   291→| `title` | no | Short summary |\n   292→| `description` | no | Full description |\n   293→| `metadata` | no | Arbitrary key-value pairs |\n   294→\n   295→The daemon picks the first task with status `open`, runs `main` with that task's ID\n   296→set in `CLOCHE_TASK_ID`, then runs `finalize` with the outcome. Tasks are\n   297→deduplicated within a timeout window to prevent rapid reassignment of the same task.\n   298→\n   299→### Host Workflow Example\n   300→\n   301→A three-phase `host.cloche`:\n   302→\n   303→```\n   304→workflow \"list-tasks\" {\n   305→  step fetch-tickets {\n   306→    run     = \"bash .cloche/scripts/ready-tasks.sh\"\n   307→    results = [success, fail]\n   308→  }\n   309→\n   310→  fetch-tickets:success -> done\n   311→  fetch-tickets:fail    -> abort\n   312→}\n   313→\n   314→workflow \"main\" {\n   315→  host {\n   316→    agent_command = \"claude\"\n   317→  }\n   318→\n   319→  step prepare-prompt {\n   320→    run     = \"bash .cloche/scripts/prepare-prompt.sh\"\n   321→    results = [success, fail]\n   322→  }\n   323→\n   324→  step develop {\n   325→    workflow_name = \"develop\"\n   326→    results       = [success, fail]\n   327→  }\n   328→\n   329→  prepare-prompt:success -> develop\n   330→  prepare-prompt:fail    -> abort\n   331→  develop:success        -> done\n   332→  develop:fail           -> done\n   333→}\n   334→\n   335→workflow \"finalize\" {\n   336→  step push-for-review {\n   337→    run     = \"bash .cloche/scripts/push-for-review.sh\"\n   338→    results = [success, fail]\n   339→  }\n   340→\n   341→  push-for-review:success -> done\n   342→  push-for-review:fail    -> done\n   343→}\n   344→```\n   345→\n   346→The `list-tasks` script writes JSONL to `$CLOCHE_STEP_OUTPUT`. The `main` workflow\n   347→receives the task ID and is responsible for claiming the ticket. The `finalize`\n   348→workflow receives `CLOCHE_MAIN_OUTCOME` and `CLOCHE_MAIN_RUN_ID` env vars to decide\n   349→what cleanup to perform.\n   350→\n   351→### Host Step Environment Variables\n   352→\n   353→| Variable | Description |\n   354→|----------|-------------|\n   355→| `CLOCHE_PROJECT_DIR` | Absolute path to the project directory on the host. |\n   356→| `CLOCHE_STEP_OUTPUT` | Path where this step should write its output (for output mappings). |\n   357→| `CLOCHE_PREV_OUTPUT` | Path to the output file from the immediately preceding step. |\n   358→| `CLOCHE_RUN_ID` | The run ID for this workflow execution. |\n   359→| `CLOCHE_TASK_ID` | Task ID assigned by the daemon (set for `main` and `finalize` phases). |\n   360→| `CLOCHE_MAIN_OUTCOME` | Result of the `main` workflow (`succeeded` or `failed`). Set for `finalize` phase only. |\n   361→| `CLOCHE_MAIN_RUN_ID` | Run ID of the completed `main` workflow. Set for `finalize` phase only. |\n   362→| Wire-mapped vars | Any env vars declared in wire output mappings. |\n   363→\n   364→### Container Environment Variables\n   365→\n   366→| Variable | Description |\n   367→|----------|-------------|\n   368→| `CLOCHE_RUN_ID` | The run ID for this workflow execution. |\n   369→| `CLOCHE_PROJECT_DIR` | Working directory (set for script steps so `cloche get`/`cloche set` work). |\n   370→| `ANTHROPIC_API_KEY` | Passed through from the host if set. |\n   371→| `CLOCHE_AGENT_COMMAND` | Overrides the default agent command inside the container. |\n   372→\n   373→## Setting Up Host Workflows\n   374→\n   375→The `host.cloche` file is the orchestration layer that ties everything together.\n   376→When you run `cloche init`, a minimal `host.cloche` with just a `main` workflow is\n   377→generated. As your project grows, you can add `list-tasks` and `finalize` workflows\n   378→to automate task discovery and cleanup.\n   379→\n   380→The daemon recognizes three workflow names in `host.cloche` and runs them in order:\n   381→\n   382→1. **`list-tasks`** — discover available work\n   383→2. **`main`** — execute the work\n   384→3. **`finalize`** — clean up after the work completes\n   385→\n   386→All three workflows live in the same `.cloche/host.cloche` file. Only `main` is\n   387→required; `list-tasks` and `finalize` are optional.\n   388→\n   389→### `list-tasks` — Discovering Work\n   390→\n   391→The `list-tasks` workflow runs first. Its job is to query your task tracker (issue\n   392→tracker, project board, ticket queue, etc.) and output a list of available tasks.\n   393→\n   394→**When it runs:** The daemon calls `list-tasks` at the start of each orchestration\n   395→loop iteration, before launching any new `main` runs.\n   396→\n   397→**Output format:** The final step must write JSONL (one JSON object per line) to\n   398→`$CLOCHE_STEP_OUTPUT`. Each line represents a task:\n   399→\n   400→```json\n   401→{\"id\": \"PROJ-42\", \"status\": \"open\", \"title\": \"Fix login bug\", \"description\": \"Users report...\"}\n   402→{\"id\": \"PROJ-43\", \"status\": \"in-progress\", \"title\": \"Add caching\", \"description\": \"...\"}\n   403→{\"id\": \"PROJ-44\", \"status\": \"open\", \"title\": \"Update docs\", \"description\": \"...\"}\n   404→```\n   405→\n   406→The daemon picks the first task with `status: \"open\"` and passes it to `main`.\n   407→Tasks that were recently assigned are deduplicated within a timeout window (default\n   408→5 minutes) to prevent the same task from being picked repeatedly.\n   409→\n   410→**How to configure:** Write a script that queries your task source and outputs JSONL:\n   411→\n   412→```\n   413→workflow \"list-tasks\" {\n   414→  step fetch-tickets {\n   415→    run     = \"bash .cloche/scripts/ready-tasks.sh\"\n   416→    results = [success, fail]\n   417→  }\n   418→\n   419→  fetch-tickets:success -> done\n   420→  fetch-tickets:fail    -> abort\n   421→}\n   422→```\n   423→\n   424→**If omitted:** The daemon falls back to single-workflow mode — it runs `main`\n   425→once without task assignment. This is fine for simple use cases where you trigger\n   426→runs manually with `cloche run`.\n   427→\n   428→### `main` — Executing Work\n   429→\n   430→The `main` workflow does the actual work. This is the only required workflow in\n   431→`host.cloche` and is always generated by `cloche init`.\n   432→\n   433→**When it runs:** After `list-tasks` selects a task (or immediately if `list-tasks`\n   434→is absent). The daemon sets the `CLOCHE_TASK_ID` environment variable from the\n   435→selected task.\n   436→\n   437→**How to configure:** A typical `main` workflow prepares a prompt from the task data,\n   438→then dispatches a container workflow:\n   439→\n   440→```\n   441→workflow \"main\" {\n   442→  host {\n   443→    agent_command = \"claude\"\n   444→  }\n   445→\n   446→  step prepare-prompt {\n   447→    run     = \"bash .cloche/scripts/prepare-prompt.sh\"\n   448→    results = [success, fail]\n   449→  }\n   450→\n   451→  step develop {\n   452→    workflow_name = \"develop\"\n   453→    prompt_step   = \"prepare-prompt\"\n   454→    results       = [success, fail]\n   455→  }\n   456→\n   457→  prepare-prompt:success -> develop\n   458→  prepare-prompt:fail    -> abort\n   459→  develop:success        -> done\n   460→  develop:fail           -> done\n   461→}\n   462→```\n   463→\n   464→The `workflow_name` step type dispatches a container workflow run and blocks until\n   465→it completes. Use `prompt_step` to specify which preceding step's output should be\n   466→used as the prompt for the container run.\n   467→\n   468→You can add steps before or after the container workflow — for example, a\n   469→`claim-task` step to mark the task as in-progress in your tracker, or a\n   470→`merge-to-main` step to merge the result branch.\n   471→\n   472→### `finalize` — Post-Run Cleanup\n   473→\n   474→The `finalize` workflow handles cleanup after `main` completes. It runs regardless\n   475→of whether `main` succeeded or failed.\n   476→\n   477→**When it runs:** Immediately after `main` finishes (success or failure). The daemon\n   478→sets two additional environment variables:\n   479→\n   480→- `CLOCHE_MAIN_OUTCOME` — `\"succeeded\"` or `\"failed\"`\n   481→- `CLOCHE_MAIN_RUN_ID` — the run ID of the completed `main` workflow\n   482→\n   483→**How to configure:** Use the outcome to decide what cleanup to perform:\n   484→\n   485→```\n   486→workflow \"finalize\" {\n   487→  step close-task {\n   488→    run     = \"bash .cloche/scripts/close-task.sh\"\n   489→    results = [success, fail]\n   490→  }\n   491→\n   492→  close-task:success -> done\n   493→  close-task:fail    -> done\n   494→}\n   495→```\n   496→\n   497→A typical `finalize` script checks `$CLOCHE_MAIN_OUTCOME` and acts accordingly —\n   498→closing the ticket on success, or posting a failure comment for investigation.\n   499→Wiring both results to `done` (not `abort`) ensures the daemon treats the\n   500→finalize phase as complete regardless of the cleanup script's exit status.\n   501→\n   502→**If omitted:** The daemon skips the finalize phase entirely. This is fine if you\n   503→don't need automated cleanup.\n   504→\n   505→### Putting It All Together\n   506→\n   507→The three-phase model enables fully automated task pipelines:\n   508→\n   509→1. The orchestration loop calls `list-tasks` to find open work\n   510→2. It picks an open task and launches `main` with the task context\n   511→3. `main` prepares a prompt, dispatches a container workflow, and optionally merges results\n   512→4. `finalize` closes the ticket or reports failure\n   513→5. The loop repeats, picking the next open task\n   514→\n   515→Start the loop with `cloche loop` and monitor tasks with `cloche tasks`. The\n   516→`--max` flag controls how many `main` runs execute concurrently.\n   517→\n   518→## Complete Example: Container Workflow with Parallel Validation\n   519→\n   520→```\n   521→workflow \"develop\" {\n   522→  step implement {\n   523→    prompt = file(\"prompts/implement.md\")\n   524→    results = [success, fail]\n   525→  }\n   526→\n   527→  step test {\n   528→    run = \"bundle exec rake test 2>&1\"\n   529→    results = [success, fail]\n   530→  }\n   531→\n   532→  step lint {\n   533→    run = \"bundle exec rubocop 2>&1\"\n   534→    results = [success, fail]\n   535→  }\n   536→\n   537→  step quality {\n   538→    run = \"python3 scripts/quality-check.py 2>&1\"\n   539→    results = [success, fail]\n   540→  }\n   541→\n   542→  step fix {\n   543→    prompt = file(\"prompts/fix.md\")\n   544→    max_attempts = \"2\"\n   545→    results = [success, fail, give-up]\n   546→  }\n   547→\n   548→  implement:success -> test\n   549→  implement:fail -> abort\n   550→\n   551→  test:success -> lint\n   552→  test:success -> quality\n   553→  test:fail -> fix\n   554→\n   555→  lint:fail -> fix\n   556→  quality:fail -> fix\n   557→  collect all(lint:success, quality:success) -> done\n   558→\n   559→  fix:success -> test\n   560→  fix:fail -> abort\n   561→  fix:give-up -> abort\n   562→}\n   563→```\n   564→\n   565→## Container Isolation Model\n   566→\n   567→- **Files in**: `docker cp` copies the project into `/workspace/`. No bind mounts. Override files from `.cloche/overrides/` are applied on top. `.git/` is included.\n   568→- **Files out**: On completion, the daemon extracts results via `docker cp` into a git worktree and commits to a `cloche/<run-id>` branch.\n   569→- **Auth files**: `~/.claude/` and `~/.claude.json` are copied into each container at `/home/agent/` for Claude Code session reuse. Copied (not bind-mounted) so each container gets its own isolated copy.\n   570→- **Network**: Containers have network access (needed for API calls).\n   571→- **Cleanup**: Containers are removed after successful runs unless `--keep-container` is set. Failed runs always keep their container.\n   572→\n   573→Your project directory is never modified by the container.\n   574→\n   575→## CLI Reference\n   576→\n   577→Every subcommand supports `--help` (or `-h`) to show detailed usage, flags, and\n   578→examples. Use `cloche help <command>` for the same output:\n   579→\n   580→```\n   581→cloche --help              # top-level overview\n   582→cloche help run            # detailed help for \"run\"\n   583→cloche run --help          # same as above\n   584→```\n   585→\n   586→### `cloche init`\n   587→\n   588→Scaffold a new Cloche project.\n   589→\n   590→```\n   591→cloche init [--workflow <name>] [--base-image <base>]\n   592→```\n   593→\n   594→| Flag | Default | Description |\n   595→|------|---------|-------------|\n   596→| `--workflow <name>` | `develop` | Workflow name. Creates `.cloche/<name>.cloche`. |\n   597→| `--base-image <base>` | `cloche-base:latest` | Base Docker image for the generated Dockerfile. |\n   598→\n   599→Creates `.cloche/` with workflow file, Dockerfile, `config.toml`, prompt templates,\n   600→host workflow (`host.cloche`), and prompt generation script. Skips existing files.\n   601→\n   602→### `cloche run`\n   603→\n   604→Launch a workflow run.\n   605→\n   606→```\n   607→cloche run --workflow <name> [--prompt \"...\"] [--title \"...\"] [--keep-container]\n   608→```\n   609→\n   610→| Flag | Description |\n   611→|------|-------------|\n   612→| `--workflow <name>` | Workflow name. Resolves to `.cloche/<name>.cloche`. |\n   613→| `--prompt \"...\"`, `-p` | Inline prompt written to `.cloche/<run-id>/prompt.txt`. |\n   614→| `--title \"...\"` | One-line summary for status display. Auto-generated if omitted. |\n   615→| `--keep-container` | Keep container on success (failed runs always keep it). |\n   616→\n   617→Must be run from inside a git repository. The daemon auto-rebuilds the Docker image\n   618→when `.cloche/Dockerfile` changes.\n   619→\n   620→### `cloche status`\n   621→\n   622→```\n   623→cloche status <run-id>\n   624→```\n   625→\n   626→Shows run title, type (`host`/`container`), state, active steps, and per-step results.\n   627→\n   628→### `cloche list`\n   629→\n   630→```\n   631→cloche list [flags]\n   632→```\n   633→\n   634→Lists runs for the current project directory. Pass `--all` to show runs across all projects.\n   635→Results can be filtered by state, project, issue, or limited to a fixed number.\n   636→\n   637→| Flag | Description |\n   638→|------|-------------|\n   639→| `--all` | Show runs from all projects (default: current project only). |\n   640→| `--project, -p DIR` | Filter by project directory. |\n   641→| `--state, -s STATE` | Filter by run state (`pending`, `running`, `succeeded`, `failed`, `cancelled`). |\n   642→| `--limit, -n NUM` | Limit the number of results returned. |\n   643→| `--issue, -i ID` | Filter by issue/task ID. |\n   644→\n   645→### `cloche logs`\n   646→\n   647→```\n   648→cloche logs <run-id> [--step <name>] [--type <full|script|llm>] [-f]\n   649→```\n   650→\n   651→| Flag | Description |\n   652→|------|-------------|\n   653→| `--step <name>` | Show only logs for the specified step. |\n   654→| `--type <full\\|script\\|llm>` | Log type filter. |\n   655→| `-f` | Follow mode: display existing logs then continue streaming new lines as they arrive (like `tail -f`). |\n   656→\n   657→Without `-f`, displays all logs captured to date and exits (even for active runs). With `-f` on an active run, existing logs are sent first, then new output is streamed in real time via gRPC until the run completes.\n   658→\n   659→### `cloche poll`\n   660→\n   661→```\n   662→cloche poll <run-id> [run-id...]\n   663→```\n   664→\n   665→Block until all specified runs finish. Polls every 2 seconds. Exits 0 if all runs succeeded, 1 if any failed or were cancelled.\n   666→\n   667→With a single run ID, prints step-level progress. With multiple run IDs, displays a compact status summary (e.g. `id1: running`) and re-prints whenever a state changes. Use `cloche logs` for detailed output of individual runs.\n   668→\n   669→### `cloche stop`\n   670→\n   671→```\n   672→cloche stop <run-id>\n   673→```\n   674→\n   675→### `cloche delete`\n   676→\n   677→```\n   678→cloche delete <container-or-run-id>\n   679→```\n   680→\n   681→Delete a retained Docker container by container ID or run ID.\n   682→\n   683→### `cloche health`\n   684→\n   685→```\n   686→cloche health\n   687→```\n   688→\n   689→Show per-project pass/fail summary. Requires `CLOCHE_HTTP`.\n   690→\n   691→### `cloche workflow`\n   692→\n   693→```\n   694→cloche workflow [--project <dir>]\n   695→cloche workflow <name> [--project <dir>]\n   696→```\n   697→\n   698→List all workflows or render a specific workflow as an ASCII-art graph.\n   699→\n   700→| Flag | Default | Description |\n   701→|------|---------|-------------|\n   702→| `--project <dir>`, `-p` | current directory | Project directory to search for workflows. |\n   703→\n   704→With no arguments, lists all workflows grouped by type (container or host). With a\n   705→workflow name, renders the workflow graph showing step boxes, wiring, and result paths.\n   706→Wires are colorized: green for `success`, red for `fail`/`failed`,\n   707→blue/yellow/orange/magenta for other results. Wires to the same destination are merged\n   708→for readability.\n   709→\n   710→### `cloche project`\n   711→\n   712→Show project info and config.\n   713→\n   714→```\n   715→cloche project [--name <label>]\n   716→```\n   717→\n   718→By default, looks up the project by the current working directory. Use `--name` to look\n   719→up a project by its registered label instead.\n   720→\n   721→| Flag | Default | Description |\n   722→|------|---------|-------------|\n   723→| `--name <label>` | _(cwd lookup)_ | Look up project by label (e.g. `cloche`) instead of directory. |\n   724→\n   725→Output includes: config settings (active, concurrency, stagger, dedup, evolution),\n   726→orchestrator loop state (running/stopped), currently active runs, and known container\n   727→and host workflow names.\n   728→\n   729→### `cloche get`\n   730→\n   731→```\n   732→cloche get <key>\n   733→```\n   734→\n   735→Get a value from the run context store (`.cloche/<run-id>/context.json`). Requires\n   736→the `CLOCHE_RUN_ID` environment variable. Uses `CLOCHE_PROJECT_DIR` if set, otherwise\n   737→the current working directory. Exits 1 if the key is not found.\n   738→\n   739→### `cloche set`\n   740→\n   741→```\n   742→cloche set <key> <value|->\n   743→```\n   744→\n   745→Set a value in the run context store (`.cloche/<run-id>/context.json`). Requires\n   746→the `CLOCHE_RUN_ID` environment variable. Uses `CLOCHE_PROJECT_DIR` if set, otherwise\n   747→the current working directory. Creates the file and directories if they don't exist.\n   748→Pass `-` as the value to read from stdin (trailing newlines are trimmed).\n   749→\n   750→### `cloche tasks`\n   751→\n   752→```\n   753→cloche tasks [--project <dir>]\n   754→```\n   755→\n   756→Show the task pipeline and assignment state for an orchestration loop. Displays\n   757→upcoming/open tasks, which tasks are assigned to which runs, and auto-assignment\n   758→state. Requires `CLOCHE_HTTP` (talks to the daemon's web API).\n   759→\n   760→| Flag | Default | Description |\n   761→|------|---------|-------------|\n   762→| `--project <dir>` | current directory name | Project to query tasks for. |\n   763→\n   764→### `cloche loop`\n   765→\n   766→Start or stop the daemon's orchestration loop. The loop automatically picks up\n   767→tasks from the pipeline and runs them.\n   768→\n   769→```\n   770→cloche loop [--max <n>]\n   771→cloche loop stop\n   772→```\n   773→\n   774→| Flag | Default | Description |\n   775→|------|---------|-------------|\n   776→| `--max <n>` | config value | Maximum concurrent runs. Defaults to the value in `.cloche/config.toml`. |\n   777→\n   778→`cloche loop stop` disables the loop. Running tasks are not cancelled.\n   779→\n   780→### `cloche --version`\n   781→\n   782→Print version information for all Cloche components.\n   783→\n   784→```\n   785→cloche -v\n   786→cloche --version\n   787→```\n   788→\n   789→Displays the CLI version, queries the running daemon for its version (via gRPC),\n   790→and runs `docker run --rm --entrypoint cloche-agent <image> -v` to get the agent\n   791→version from the project's container image. If the daemon is unreachable or the\n   792→image doesn't exist, the corresponding version shows `<unavailable>`. Version\n   793→mismatches between components produce warnings on stderr.\n   794→\n   795→The daemon and agent binaries also support standalone version output:\n   796→\n   797→```\n   798→cloched -v       # prints daemon version\n   799→cloche-agent -v  # prints agent version\n   800→```\n   801→\n   802→### `cloche shutdown`\n   803→\n   804→```\n   805→cloche shutdown\n   806→```\n   807→\n   808→## Project Layout\n   809→\n   810→```\n   811→my-project/\n   812→├── .cloche/\n   813→│   ├── develop.cloche        # Container workflow\n   814→│   ├── host.cloche           # Host orchestration workflow\n   815→│   ├── Dockerfile            # Container image definition\n   816→│   ├── config.toml           # Project configuration\n   817→│   ├── prompts/              # Prompt templates\n   818→│   │   ├── implement.md\n   819→│   │   ├── fix.md\n   820→│   │   └── update-docs.md\n   821→│   ├── scripts/              # Host-side scripts\n   822→│   ├── overrides/            # Files copied on top of /workspace/\n   823→│   │   └── CLAUDE.md         # Container-specific CLAUDE.md (optional)\n   824→│   └── <run-id>/             # Runtime state (gitignored)\n   825→│       ├── prompt.txt        # User prompt\n   826→│       ├── context.json      # Shared key-value store (cloche get/set)\n   827→│       ├── output/\n   828→│       │   ├── full.log      # Unified log\n   829→│       │   ├── test.log      # Per-step script output\n   830→│       │   └── llm-impl.log  # Per-step LLM conversation\n   831→│       ├── attempt_count/    # Retry counters for max_attempts\n   832→│       └── history.log       # Step execution log\n   833→├── src/                      # Project source (untouched by Cloche)\n   834→└── .git/\n   835→```\n   836→\n   837→## Daemon Configuration\n   838→\n   839→| Variable | Default | Description |\n   840→|----------|---------|-------------|\n   841→| `CLOCHE_LISTEN` | `unix:///tmp/cloche.sock` | Listen address |\n   842→| `CLOCHE_DB` | `cloche.db` | SQLite database path |\n   843→| `CLOCHE_RUNTIME` | `docker` | `docker` or `local` (subprocess, for dev only) |\n   844→| `CLOCHE_IMAGE` | `cloche-agent:latest` | Default Docker image |\n   845→| `CLOCHE_HTTP` | _(unset)_ | HTTP address for web dashboard. Not started unless set. |\n   846→| `CLOCHE_AGENT_PATH` | _(auto)_ | Path to `cloche-agent` binary (local runtime) |\n   847→| `CLOCHE_LLM_COMMAND` | _(unset)_ | Command for LLM calls (evolution, merge conflicts) |\n   848→| `ANTHROPIC_API_KEY` | _(unset)_ | Passed into Docker containers |\n   849→| `CLOCHE_EXTRA_MOUNTS` | _(unset)_ | Extra bind mounts (comma-separated `host:container`) |\n   850→| `CLOCHE_EXTRA_ENV` | _(unset)_ | Extra env vars (comma-separated `KEY=VALUE`) |\n   851→\n   852→### Client Configuration\n   853→\n   854→| Variable | Default | Description |\n   855→|----------|---------|-------------|\n   856→| `CLOCHE_ADDR` | `unix:///tmp/cloche.sock` | Daemon gRPC address |\n   857→| `CLOCHE_HTTP` | `localhost:8080` | Daemon HTTP address |\n   858→\n   859→## Dockerfile Requirements\n   860→\n   861→The container image must have:\n   862→- `cloche-agent` binary at `/usr/local/bin/cloche-agent`\n   863→- `git` installed\n   864→- An `agent` user (cloche wraps commands with `chown` + `su agent`)\n   865→- `/workspace` as the working directory\n   866→- Your project's build dependencies and the agent binary (e.g. `claude`)\n   867→\n   868→## Build Commands\n   869→\n   870→```\n   871→make build          # Build all binaries to bin/\n   872→make test           # Run all tests\n   873→make test-short     # Run tests (skip slow ones)\n   874→make lint           # Run go vet\n   875→make proto          # Regenerate gRPC code from protobuf\n   876→make docker-build   # Build the cloche-agent Docker image\n   877→make install        # Build, install to ~/.local/bin/, restart daemon\n   878→make clean          # Remove bin/\n   879→```\n   880→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"0a1eb545-c5fc-4d99-8df4-f479f783e58f","uuid":"9e8501ca-0e93-4af5-860f-a3ad2a5007ac","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/workspace/docs/USAGE.md","content":"# Cloche Usage\n\nCloche runs containerized workflows for autonomous coding agents. You define a\nworkflow graph in the `.cloche` DSL, Cloche copies your project into a Docker\ncontainer, runs the workflow steps (agent prompts and shell scripts), and extracts\nresults to a git branch.\n\n## Core Concepts\n\n- **Workflow**: A directed graph of steps connected by named-result wiring.\n- **Step**: A unit of work. Type is inferred: `prompt` = agent step, `run` = script step, `workflow_name` = workflow step (host only).\n- **Result**: A named outcome reported by a step (e.g. `success`, `fail`, `needs-research`). Steps declare their possible results; the engine follows wiring based on the reported result.\n- **Wiring**: Maps `step:result` pairs to the next step. Separate from step definitions.\n- **Terminals**: `done` (success) and `abort` (failure) are built-in terminal targets.\n\n## Workflow DSL\n\nWorkflow files use the `.cloche` extension and live in `.cloche/`. The first step\ndeclared is the entry point. Graphs are validated at parse time (all results wired,\nno orphans, entry point exists).\n\n### Minimal Example\n\n```\nworkflow \"develop\" {\n  step implement {\n    prompt = file(\".cloche/prompts/implement.md\")\n    results = [success, fail]\n  }\n\n  step test {\n    run = \"make test 2>&1\"\n    results = [success, fail]\n  }\n\n  implement:success -> test\n  implement:fail -> abort\n  test:success -> done\n  test:fail -> abort\n}\n```\n\n### Step Configuration\n\n| Key | Type | Description |\n|-----|------|-------------|\n| `prompt` | string or `file(\"path\")` | Prompt template. Makes this an agent step. |\n| `run` | string | Shell command. Makes this a script step. |\n| `workflow_name` | string | Container workflow to dispatch. Makes this a workflow step (host only). |\n| `results` | ident list | Declared result names, e.g. `[success, fail, give-up]`. |\n| `max_attempts` | string | Max retries before automatic `give-up` result, e.g. `\"2\"`. |\n| `timeout` | string | Step timeout as Go duration, e.g. `\"30m\"`, `\"2h\"`. Default: 30m. |\n| `agent_command` | string | Agent binary name(s), comma-separated for fallback chains, e.g. `\"claude,gemini\"`. |\n| `agent_args` | string | Override default agent arguments. |\n| `feedback` | string | Set to `\"true\"` to include `.cloche/output/*.log` content in the prompt. |\n| `prompt_step` | string | For workflow steps: which preceding step's output to use as the prompt. |\n\nA step must have exactly one of `prompt`, `run`, or `workflow_name`.\n\n### The `file()` Function\n\n`file(\"path\")` reads the file at the given path relative to the working directory\n(`/workspace/` in containers) at execution time, not parse time. Use it for prompt\ntemplates:\n\n```\nprompt = file(\".cloche/prompts/implement.md\")\n```\n\n### The `container {}` Block\n\nCan appear at step level or workflow level. Keys are stored with a `container.` prefix.\n\n**Step level** — per-step container config:\n```\nstep code {\n  prompt = file(\".cloche/prompts/implement.md\")\n  container {\n    image         = \"custom-agent:v2\"\n    memory        = \"4g\"\n    network_allow = [\"docs.python.org\", \"api.example.com\"]\n  }\n  results = [success, fail]\n}\n```\n\n**Workflow level** — defaults for all steps:\n```\nworkflow \"develop\" {\n  container {\n    agent_command = \"gemini\"\n    image         = \"myregistry/myimage:v2\"\n    memory        = \"4g\"\n  }\n  ...\n}\n```\n\nSupported keys: `image`, `memory`, `network_allow`, `agent_command`, `agent_args`.\n\n### The `host {}` Block\n\nCan appear at workflow level in host workflows (`.cloche/host.cloche`). Keys are stored\nwith a `host.` prefix. Configures agent defaults for agent steps running on the host.\n\n```\nworkflow \"main\" {\n  host {\n    agent_command = \"claude\"\n  }\n  ...\n}\n```\n\nSupported keys: `agent_command`, `agent_args`. Step-level `agent_command` and\n`agent_args` config keys override the workflow-level `host {}` defaults.\n\n### Wiring Syntax\n\nConnect steps with `step:result -> next_step`:\n\n```\nimplement:success -> test\nimplement:fail -> abort\ntest:success -> done\ntest:fail -> fix\n```\n\n### Wire Output Mappings\n\nExtract values from a step's JSON output and inject as env vars into the target:\n\n```\nstep-a:success -> step-b [ ENV_VAR = output.field, OTHER = output.list[0].name ]\n```\n\nPath expressions:\n\n| Expression | Meaning |\n|---|---|\n| `output` | Raw output (full string) |\n| `output.key` | JSON object field access |\n| `output[N]` | JSON array index (0-based) |\n| `output.a.b.c` | Deeply nested field access |\n| `output.items[0].name` | Mixed field and index chaining |\n\nIf the output is valid JSON, path expressions navigate the structure. If it's plain\ntext, only bare `output` works.\n\n### Retry Loops\n\nWire failures back to earlier steps:\n\n```\ntest:fail -> fix\nfix:success -> test    // retry the test\nfix:fail -> abort\n```\n\nUse `max_attempts` to cap retries. When exhausted, the step returns `give-up`:\n\n```\nstep fix {\n  prompt = file(\".cloche/prompts/fix.md\")\n  max_attempts = \"2\"\n  results = [success, fail, give-up]\n}\n```\n\n### Parallel Branches (Fanout)\n\nWire one result to multiple targets for concurrent execution:\n\n```\ntest:success -> lint\ntest:success -> quality\n```\n\n### Collect (Join)\n\nSynchronize parallel branches:\n\n```\ncollect all(lint:success, quality:success) -> done\ncollect any(lint:success, quality:success) -> done\n```\n\n`all` fires when every condition is met. `any` fires when at least one is.\n\n### Comments\n\nLine comments with `//`:\n\n```\n// This is a comment\nimplement:success -> test  // inline comment\n```\n\n## Result Protocol\n\nSteps report results by printing a marker line to stdout:\n\n```\nCLOCHE_RESULT:<name>\n```\n\nFor example: `CLOCHE_RESULT:success`, `CLOCHE_RESULT:needs-research`, `CLOCHE_RESULT:give-up`.\n\nRules:\n- The **last** `CLOCHE_RESULT:` line wins if multiple are printed.\n- Marker lines are **stripped** from captured output (not passed to logs or downstream steps).\n- The result name must match one of the step's declared `results`.\n- For script steps with no marker: exit 0 = `success`, exit non-zero = `fail`.\n- For agent steps: if exit non-zero with a marker, the marker result is used. If exit non-zero without a marker, falls back to the next agent in the fallback chain (or returns `fail` if last).\n\n## Prompt Assembly\n\nWhen an agent step runs, Cloche assembles a prompt from these sections (joined by blank lines):\n\n1. **Step template**: The step's `prompt` content (inline string or resolved `file(\"path\")`).\n2. **User request**: Content of `.cloche/<run-id>/prompt.txt` (set via `--prompt` flag), prefixed with `## User Request`.\n3. **Validation output** (opt-in): If `feedback = \"true\"`, reads all `.log` files from `.cloche/output/` and includes them prefixed with `## Validation Output`.\n4. **Result selection**: Lists the step's declared results with instructions to print exactly one `CLOCHE_RESULT:<name>` marker.\n\nThe assembled prompt is passed to the agent command via stdin.\n\n## Agent Command Resolution\n\nPriority (highest to lowest):\n1. Step-level `agent_command`\n2. Workflow-level config block (`container { agent_command }` for container workflows, `host { agent_command }` for host workflows)\n3. `CLOCHE_AGENT_COMMAND` environment variable\n4. Default: `claude`\n\n### Fallback Chains\n\nComma-separated commands are tried in order:\n\n```\nagent_command = \"claude,gemini,codex\"\n```\n\n- **Command not found / failed to start** — try next command\n- **Exit non-zero without `CLOCHE_RESULT` marker** — try next command\n- **Exit non-zero with `CLOCHE_RESULT` marker** — use that result (no fallback)\n- **Exit 0** — use result (no fallback)\n- **All commands fail to start** — step returns an error\n- **Last command crashes without marker** — step returns `fail`\n\nKnown agents (e.g. `claude`) get default arguments (`-p --output-format stream-json --verbose --dangerously-skip-permissions`). Unknown agents receive the prompt on stdin with no flags. Override with `agent_args`.\n\n### Agent Setup Guides\n\nFor detailed container setup instructions per agent:\n\n- [How to set up Claude Code](agent-setup-claude.md) — session-based auth, no API key needed\n- [How to set up Codex](agent-setup-codex.md) — API key configuration\n\n## Workflow Locations\n\n**Container workflows** (`.cloche/*.cloche` except `host.cloche`) run inside Docker\nvia `cloche-agent`. Steps may only be `agent` or `script` type.\n\n**Host workflow** (`.cloche/host.cloche`) runs on the host machine as the daemon.\nSteps may be `agent`, `script`, or `workflow` type. The `workflow_name` step type\ndispatches a container workflow run and blocks until it completes. Script steps\nexecute with their working directory set to the main git worktree, so host-workflow\nfixes on main are available to in-flight runs even if they branched earlier.\n\nA single `host.cloche` file may contain **multiple named workflows**. The daemon\nuses up to three workflow phases for orchestration:\n\n| Phase | Workflow name | Purpose |\n|-------|--------------|---------|\n| 1 | `list-tasks` | Discover available work. Output is JSONL (one task per line). |\n| 2 | `main` | Do the work. Receives a task ID via `CLOCHE_TASK_ID` env var. |\n| 3 | `finalize` | Post-main cleanup. Runs on **both** success and failure. |\n\nOnly `main` is required. If `list-tasks` is absent, the daemon uses a single-workflow\nmode. If `finalize` is absent, it is skipped.\n\n### list-tasks Output Format\n\nThe `list-tasks` workflow's final step output is parsed as JSONL. Each line is a JSON\nobject:\n\n| Field | Required | Description |\n|-------|----------|-------------|\n| `id` | yes | Unique task identifier |\n| `status` | yes | One of `open`, `closed`, `in-progress` |\n| `title` | no | Short summary |\n| `description` | no | Full description |\n| `metadata` | no | Arbitrary key-value pairs |\n\nThe daemon picks the first task with status `open`, runs `main` with that task's ID\nset in `CLOCHE_TASK_ID`, then runs `finalize` with the outcome. Tasks are\ndeduplicated within a timeout window to prevent rapid reassignment of the same task.\n\n### Host Workflow Example\n\nA three-phase `host.cloche`:\n\n```\nworkflow \"list-tasks\" {\n  step fetch-tickets {\n    run     = \"bash .cloche/scripts/ready-tasks.sh\"\n    results = [success, fail]\n  }\n\n  fetch-tickets:success -> done\n  fetch-tickets:fail    -> abort\n}\n\nworkflow \"main\" {\n  host {\n    agent_command = \"claude\"\n  }\n\n  step prepare-prompt {\n    run     = \"bash .cloche/scripts/prepare-prompt.sh\"\n    results = [success, fail]\n  }\n\n  step develop {\n    workflow_name = \"develop\"\n    results       = [success, fail]\n  }\n\n  prepare-prompt:success -> develop\n  prepare-prompt:fail    -> abort\n  develop:success        -> done\n  develop:fail           -> done\n}\n\nworkflow \"finalize\" {\n  step push-for-review {\n    run     = \"bash .cloche/scripts/push-for-review.sh\"\n    results = [success, fail]\n  }\n\n  push-for-review:success -> done\n  push-for-review:fail    -> done\n}\n```\n\nThe `list-tasks` script writes JSONL to `$CLOCHE_STEP_OUTPUT`. The `main` workflow\nreceives the task ID and is responsible for claiming the ticket. The `finalize`\nworkflow receives `CLOCHE_MAIN_OUTCOME` and `CLOCHE_MAIN_RUN_ID` env vars to decide\nwhat cleanup to perform.\n\n### Host Step Environment Variables\n\n| Variable | Description |\n|----------|-------------|\n| `CLOCHE_PROJECT_DIR` | Absolute path to the project directory on the host. |\n| `CLOCHE_STEP_OUTPUT` | Path where this step should write its output (for output mappings). |\n| `CLOCHE_PREV_OUTPUT` | Path to the output file from the immediately preceding step. |\n| `CLOCHE_RUN_ID` | The run ID for this workflow execution. |\n| `CLOCHE_TASK_ID` | Task ID assigned by the daemon (set for `main` and `finalize` phases). |\n| `CLOCHE_MAIN_OUTCOME` | Result of the `main` workflow (`succeeded` or `failed`). Set for `finalize` phase only. |\n| `CLOCHE_MAIN_RUN_ID` | Run ID of the completed `main` workflow. Set for `finalize` phase only. |\n| Wire-mapped vars | Any env vars declared in wire output mappings. |\n\n### Container Environment Variables\n\n| Variable | Description |\n|----------|-------------|\n| `CLOCHE_RUN_ID` | The run ID for this workflow execution. |\n| `CLOCHE_PROJECT_DIR` | Working directory (set for script steps so `cloche get`/`cloche set` work). |\n| `ANTHROPIC_API_KEY` | Passed through from the host if set. |\n| `CLOCHE_AGENT_COMMAND` | Overrides the default agent command inside the container. |\n\n## Setting Up Host Workflows\n\nThe `host.cloche` file is the orchestration layer that ties everything together.\nWhen you run `cloche init`, a minimal `host.cloche` with just a `main` workflow is\ngenerated. As your project grows, you can add `list-tasks` and `finalize` workflows\nto automate task discovery and cleanup.\n\nThe daemon recognizes three workflow names in `host.cloche` and runs them in order:\n\n1. **`list-tasks`** — discover available work\n2. **`main`** — execute the work\n3. **`finalize`** — clean up after the work completes\n\nAll three workflows live in the same `.cloche/host.cloche` file. Only `main` is\nrequired; `list-tasks` and `finalize` are optional.\n\n### `list-tasks` — Discovering Work\n\nThe `list-tasks` workflow runs first. Its job is to query your task tracker (issue\ntracker, project board, ticket queue, etc.) and output a list of available tasks.\n\n**When it runs:** The daemon calls `list-tasks` at the start of each orchestration\nloop iteration, before launching any new `main` runs.\n\n**Output format:** The final step must write JSONL (one JSON object per line) to\n`$CLOCHE_STEP_OUTPUT`. Each line represents a task:\n\n```json\n{\"id\": \"PROJ-42\", \"status\": \"open\", \"title\": \"Fix login bug\", \"description\": \"Users report...\"}\n{\"id\": \"PROJ-43\", \"status\": \"in-progress\", \"title\": \"Add caching\", \"description\": \"...\"}\n{\"id\": \"PROJ-44\", \"status\": \"open\", \"title\": \"Update docs\", \"description\": \"...\"}\n```\n\nThe daemon picks the first task with `status: \"open\"` and passes it to `main`.\nTasks that were recently assigned are deduplicated within a timeout window (default\n5 minutes) to prevent the same task from being picked repeatedly.\n\n**How to configure:** Write a script that queries your task source and outputs JSONL:\n\n```\nworkflow \"list-tasks\" {\n  step fetch-tickets {\n    run     = \"bash .cloche/scripts/ready-tasks.sh\"\n    results = [success, fail]\n  }\n\n  fetch-tickets:success -> done\n  fetch-tickets:fail    -> abort\n}\n```\n\n**If omitted:** The daemon falls back to single-workflow mode — it runs `main`\nonce without task assignment. This is fine for simple use cases where you trigger\nruns manually with `cloche run`.\n\n### `main` — Executing Work\n\nThe `main` workflow does the actual work. This is the only required workflow in\n`host.cloche` and is always generated by `cloche init`.\n\n**When it runs:** After `list-tasks` selects a task (or immediately if `list-tasks`\nis absent). The daemon sets the `CLOCHE_TASK_ID` environment variable from the\nselected task.\n\n**How to configure:** A typical `main` workflow prepares a prompt from the task data,\nthen dispatches a container workflow:\n\n```\nworkflow \"main\" {\n  host {\n    agent_command = \"claude\"\n  }\n\n  step prepare-prompt {\n    run     = \"bash .cloche/scripts/prepare-prompt.sh\"\n    results = [success, fail]\n  }\n\n  step develop {\n    workflow_name = \"develop\"\n    prompt_step   = \"prepare-prompt\"\n    results       = [success, fail]\n  }\n\n  prepare-prompt:success -> develop\n  prepare-prompt:fail    -> abort\n  develop:success        -> done\n  develop:fail           -> done\n}\n```\n\nThe `workflow_name` step type dispatches a container workflow run and blocks until\nit completes. Use `prompt_step` to specify which preceding step's output should be\nused as the prompt for the container run.\n\nYou can add steps before or after the container workflow — for example, a\n`claim-task` step to mark the task as in-progress in your tracker, or a\n`merge-to-main` step to merge the result branch.\n\n### `finalize` — Post-Run Cleanup\n\nThe `finalize` workflow handles cleanup after `main` completes. It runs regardless\nof whether `main` succeeded or failed.\n\n**When it runs:** Immediately after `main` finishes (success or failure). The daemon\nsets two additional environment variables:\n\n- `CLOCHE_MAIN_OUTCOME` — `\"succeeded\"` or `\"failed\"`\n- `CLOCHE_MAIN_RUN_ID` — the run ID of the completed `main` workflow\n\n**How to configure:** Use the outcome to decide what cleanup to perform:\n\n```\nworkflow \"finalize\" {\n  step close-task {\n    run     = \"bash .cloche/scripts/close-task.sh\"\n    results = [success, fail]\n  }\n\n  close-task:success -> done\n  close-task:fail    -> done\n}\n```\n\nA typical `finalize` script checks `$CLOCHE_MAIN_OUTCOME` and acts accordingly —\nclosing the ticket on success, or posting a failure comment for investigation.\nWiring both results to `done` (not `abort`) ensures the daemon treats the\nfinalize phase as complete regardless of the cleanup script's exit status.\n\n**If omitted:** The daemon skips the finalize phase entirely. This is fine if you\ndon't need automated cleanup.\n\n### Putting It All Together\n\nThe three-phase model enables fully automated task pipelines:\n\n1. The orchestration loop calls `list-tasks` to find open work\n2. It picks an open task and launches `main` with the task context\n3. `main` prepares a prompt, dispatches a container workflow, and optionally merges results\n4. `finalize` closes the ticket or reports failure\n5. The loop repeats, picking the next open task\n\nStart the loop with `cloche loop` and monitor tasks with `cloche tasks`. The\n`--max` flag controls how many `main` runs execute concurrently.\n\n## Complete Example: Container Workflow with Parallel Validation\n\n```\nworkflow \"develop\" {\n  step implement {\n    prompt = file(\"prompts/implement.md\")\n    results = [success, fail]\n  }\n\n  step test {\n    run = \"bundle exec rake test 2>&1\"\n    results = [success, fail]\n  }\n\n  step lint {\n    run = \"bundle exec rubocop 2>&1\"\n    results = [success, fail]\n  }\n\n  step quality {\n    run = \"python3 scripts/quality-check.py 2>&1\"\n    results = [success, fail]\n  }\n\n  step fix {\n    prompt = file(\"prompts/fix.md\")\n    max_attempts = \"2\"\n    results = [success, fail, give-up]\n  }\n\n  implement:success -> test\n  implement:fail -> abort\n\n  test:success -> lint\n  test:success -> quality\n  test:fail -> fix\n\n  lint:fail -> fix\n  quality:fail -> fix\n  collect all(lint:success, quality:success) -> done\n\n  fix:success -> test\n  fix:fail -> abort\n  fix:give-up -> abort\n}\n```\n\n## Container Isolation Model\n\n- **Files in**: `docker cp` copies the project into `/workspace/`. No bind mounts. Override files from `.cloche/overrides/` are applied on top. `.git/` is included.\n- **Files out**: On completion, the daemon extracts results via `docker cp` into a git worktree and commits to a `cloche/<run-id>` branch.\n- **Auth files**: `~/.claude/` and `~/.claude.json` are copied into each container at `/home/agent/` for Claude Code session reuse. Copied (not bind-mounted) so each container gets its own isolated copy.\n- **Network**: Containers have network access (needed for API calls).\n- **Cleanup**: Containers are removed after successful runs unless `--keep-container` is set. Failed runs always keep their container.\n\nYour project directory is never modified by the container.\n\n## CLI Reference\n\nEvery subcommand supports `--help` (or `-h`) to show detailed usage, flags, and\nexamples. Use `cloche help <command>` for the same output:\n\n```\ncloche --help              # top-level overview\ncloche help run            # detailed help for \"run\"\ncloche run --help          # same as above\n```\n\n### `cloche init`\n\nScaffold a new Cloche project.\n\n```\ncloche init [--workflow <name>] [--base-image <base>]\n```\n\n| Flag | Default | Description |\n|------|---------|-------------|\n| `--workflow <name>` | `develop` | Workflow name. Creates `.cloche/<name>.cloche`. |\n| `--base-image <base>` | `cloche-base:latest` | Base Docker image for the generated Dockerfile. |\n\nCreates `.cloche/` with workflow file, Dockerfile, `config.toml`, prompt templates,\nhost workflow (`host.cloche`), and prompt generation script. Skips existing files.\n\n### `cloche run`\n\nLaunch a workflow run.\n\n```\ncloche run --workflow <name> [--prompt \"...\"] [--title \"...\"] [--keep-container]\n```\n\n| Flag | Description |\n|------|-------------|\n| `--workflow <name>` | Workflow name. Resolves to `.cloche/<name>.cloche`. |\n| `--prompt \"...\"`, `-p` | Inline prompt written to `.cloche/<run-id>/prompt.txt`. |\n| `--title \"...\"` | One-line summary for status display. Auto-generated if omitted. |\n| `--keep-container` | Keep container on success (failed runs always keep it). |\n\nMust be run from inside a git repository. The daemon auto-rebuilds the Docker image\nwhen `.cloche/Dockerfile` changes.\n\n### `cloche status`\n\n```\ncloche status <run-id>\n```\n\nShows run title, type (`host`/`container`), state, active steps, and per-step results.\n\n### `cloche list`\n\n```\ncloche list [flags]\n```\n\nLists runs for the current project directory. Pass `--all` to show runs across all projects.\nResults can be filtered by state, project, issue, or limited to a fixed number.\n\n| Flag | Description |\n|------|-------------|\n| `--all` | Show runs from all projects (default: current project only). |\n| `--project, -p DIR` | Filter by project directory. |\n| `--state, -s STATE` | Filter by run state (`pending`, `running`, `succeeded`, `failed`, `cancelled`). |\n| `--limit, -n NUM` | Limit the number of results returned. |\n| `--issue, -i ID` | Filter by issue/task ID. |\n\n### `cloche logs`\n\n```\ncloche logs <run-id> [--step <name>] [--type <full|script|llm>] [-f]\n```\n\n| Flag | Description |\n|------|-------------|\n| `--step <name>` | Show only logs for the specified step. |\n| `--type <full\\|script\\|llm>` | Log type filter. |\n| `-f` | Follow mode: display existing logs then continue streaming new lines as they arrive (like `tail -f`). |\n\nWithout `-f`, displays all logs captured to date and exits (even for active runs). With `-f` on an active run, existing logs are sent first, then new output is streamed in real time via gRPC until the run completes.\n\n### `cloche poll`\n\n```\ncloche poll <run-id> [run-id...]\n```\n\nBlock until all specified runs finish. Polls every 2 seconds. Exits 0 if all runs succeeded, 1 if any failed or were cancelled.\n\nWith a single run ID, prints step-level progress. With multiple run IDs, displays a compact status summary (e.g. `id1: running`) and re-prints whenever a state changes. Use `cloche logs` for detailed output of individual runs.\n\n### `cloche stop`\n\n```\ncloche stop <run-id>\n```\n\n### `cloche delete`\n\n```\ncloche delete <container-or-run-id>\n```\n\nDelete a retained Docker container by container ID or run ID.\n\n### `cloche health`\n\n```\ncloche health\n```\n\nShow per-project pass/fail summary. Requires `CLOCHE_HTTP`.\n\n### `cloche workflow`\n\n```\ncloche workflow [--project <dir>]\ncloche workflow <name> [--project <dir>]\n```\n\nList all workflows or render a specific workflow as an ASCII-art graph.\n\n| Flag | Default | Description |\n|------|---------|-------------|\n| `--project <dir>`, `-p` | current directory | Project directory to search for workflows. |\n\nWith no arguments, lists all workflows grouped by type (container or host). With a\nworkflow name, renders the workflow graph showing step boxes, wiring, and result paths.\nWires are colorized: green for `success`, red for `fail`/`failed`,\nblue/yellow/orange/magenta for other results. Wires to the same destination are merged\nfor readability.\n\n### `cloche project`\n\nShow project info and config.\n\n```\ncloche project [--name <label>]\n```\n\nBy default, looks up the project by the current working directory. Use `--name` to look\nup a project by its registered label instead.\n\n| Flag | Default | Description |\n|------|---------|-------------|\n| `--name <label>` | _(cwd lookup)_ | Look up project by label (e.g. `cloche`) instead of directory. |\n\nOutput includes: config settings (active, concurrency, stagger, dedup, evolution),\norchestrator loop state (running/stopped), currently active runs, and known container\nand host workflow names.\n\n### `cloche get`\n\n```\ncloche get <key>\n```\n\nGet a value from the run context store (`.cloche/<run-id>/context.json`). Requires\nthe `CLOCHE_RUN_ID` environment variable. Uses `CLOCHE_PROJECT_DIR` if set, otherwise\nthe current working directory. Exits 1 if the key is not found.\n\n### `cloche set`\n\n```\ncloche set <key> <value|->\n```\n\nSet a value in the run context store (`.cloche/<run-id>/context.json`). Requires\nthe `CLOCHE_RUN_ID` environment variable. Uses `CLOCHE_PROJECT_DIR` if set, otherwise\nthe current working directory. Creates the file and directories if they don't exist.\nPass `-` as the value to read from stdin (trailing newlines are trimmed).\n\n### `cloche tasks`\n\n```\ncloche tasks [--project <dir>]\n```\n\nShow the task pipeline and assignment state for an orchestration loop. Displays\nupcoming/open tasks, which tasks are assigned to which runs, and auto-assignment\nstate. Requires `CLOCHE_HTTP` (talks to the daemon's web API).\n\n| Flag | Default | Description |\n|------|---------|-------------|\n| `--project <dir>` | current directory name | Project to query tasks for. |\n\n### `cloche loop`\n\nStart or stop the daemon's orchestration loop. The loop automatically picks up\ntasks from the pipeline and runs them.\n\n```\ncloche loop [--max <n>]\ncloche loop stop\n```\n\n| Flag | Default | Description |\n|------|---------|-------------|\n| `--max <n>` | config value | Maximum concurrent runs. Defaults to the value in `.cloche/config.toml`. |\n\n`cloche loop stop` disables the loop. Running tasks are not cancelled.\n\n### `cloche --version`\n\nPrint version information for all Cloche components.\n\n```\ncloche -v\ncloche --version\n```\n\nDisplays the CLI version, queries the running daemon for its version (via gRPC),\nand runs `docker run --rm --entrypoint cloche-agent <image> -v` to get the agent\nversion from the project's container image. If the daemon is unreachable or the\nimage doesn't exist, the corresponding version shows `<unavailable>`. Version\nmismatches between components produce warnings on stderr.\n\nThe daemon and agent binaries also support standalone version output:\n\n```\ncloched -v       # prints daemon version\ncloche-agent -v  # prints agent version\n```\n\n### `cloche shutdown`\n\n```\ncloche shutdown\n```\n\n## Project Layout\n\n```\nmy-project/\n├── .cloche/\n│   ├── develop.cloche        # Container workflow\n│   ├── host.cloche           # Host orchestration workflow\n│   ├── Dockerfile            # Container image definition\n│   ├── config.toml           # Project configuration\n│   ├── prompts/              # Prompt templates\n│   │   ├── implement.md\n│   │   ├── fix.md\n│   │   └── update-docs.md\n│   ├── scripts/              # Host-side scripts\n│   ├── overrides/            # Files copied on top of /workspace/\n│   │   └── CLAUDE.md         # Container-specific CLAUDE.md (optional)\n│   └── <run-id>/             # Runtime state (gitignored)\n│       ├── prompt.txt        # User prompt\n│       ├── context.json      # Shared key-value store (cloche get/set)\n│       ├── output/\n│       │   ├── full.log      # Unified log\n│       │   ├── test.log      # Per-step script output\n│       │   └── llm-impl.log  # Per-step LLM conversation\n│       ├── attempt_count/    # Retry counters for max_attempts\n│       └── history.log       # Step execution log\n├── src/                      # Project source (untouched by Cloche)\n└── .git/\n```\n\n## Daemon Configuration\n\n| Variable | Default | Description |\n|----------|---------|-------------|\n| `CLOCHE_LISTEN` | `unix:///tmp/cloche.sock` | Listen address |\n| `CLOCHE_DB` | `cloche.db` | SQLite database path |\n| `CLOCHE_RUNTIME` | `docker` | `docker` or `local` (subprocess, for dev only) |\n| `CLOCHE_IMAGE` | `cloche-agent:latest` | Default Docker image |\n| `CLOCHE_HTTP` | _(unset)_ | HTTP address for web dashboard. Not started unless set. |\n| `CLOCHE_AGENT_PATH` | _(auto)_ | Path to `cloche-agent` binary (local runtime) |\n| `CLOCHE_LLM_COMMAND` | _(unset)_ | Command for LLM calls (evolution, merge conflicts) |\n| `ANTHROPIC_API_KEY` | _(unset)_ | Passed into Docker containers |\n| `CLOCHE_EXTRA_MOUNTS` | _(unset)_ | Extra bind mounts (comma-separated `host:container`) |\n| `CLOCHE_EXTRA_ENV` | _(unset)_ | Extra env vars (comma-separated `KEY=VALUE`) |\n\n### Client Configuration\n\n| Variable | Default | Description |\n|----------|---------|-------------|\n| `CLOCHE_ADDR` | `unix:///tmp/cloche.sock` | Daemon gRPC address |\n| `CLOCHE_HTTP` | `localhost:8080` | Daemon HTTP address |\n\n## Dockerfile Requirements\n\nThe container image must have:\n- `cloche-agent` binary at `/usr/local/bin/cloche-agent`\n- `git` installed\n- An `agent` user (cloche wraps commands with `chown` + `su agent`)\n- `/workspace` as the working directory\n- Your project's build dependencies and the agent binary (e.g. `claude`)\n\n## Build Commands\n\n```\nmake build          # Build all binaries to bin/\nmake test           # Run all tests\nmake test-short     # Run tests (skip slow ones)\nmake lint           # Run go vet\nmake proto          # Regenerate gRPC code from protobuf\nmake docker-build   # Build the cloche-agent Docker image\nmake install        # Build, install to ~/.local/bin/, restart daemon\nmake clean          # Remove bin/\n```\n","numLines":880,"startLine":1,"totalLines":880}}}
