{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_011FJybb9STAj5x4Y2FM2Y6x","type":"tool_result","content":"    16→point for custom orchestration strategies.\n    17→\n    18→A single `host.cloche` file may contain **multiple named workflows**. The daemon\n    19→uses up to three workflow phases for orchestration:\n    20→\n    21→| Phase | Workflow name | Purpose |\n    22→|-------|--------------|---------|\n    23→| 1 | `list-tasks` | Discover available work. Output is JSONL (one task per line). |\n    24→| 2 | `main` | Do the work. Receives a task ID via `CLOCHE_TASK_ID` env var. |\n    25→| 3 | `finalize` | Post-main cleanup. Runs on **both** success and failure. |\n    26→\n    27→Additionally, `host.cloche` may define a **`release-task`** utility workflow. This is\n    28→not part of the automatic orchestration loop — it is invoked on demand (e.g. from the\n    29→web dashboard) to release a stale claimed task back to `open` status. Receives\n    30→`CLOCHE_TASK_ID` for the task to release.\n    31→\n    32→Only `main` is required. If `list-tasks` is absent, the daemon uses a legacy\n    33→single-function mode. If `finalize` is absent, it is skipped.\n    34→\n    35→The `list-tasks` workflow's final step output is parsed as JSONL. Each line is a JSON"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"0a1eb545-c5fc-4d99-8df4-f479f783e58f","uuid":"0535b737-6118-4134-a7ce-288789c37926","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/workspace/docs/workflows.md","content":"point for custom orchestration strategies.\n\nA single `host.cloche` file may contain **multiple named workflows**. The daemon\nuses up to three workflow phases for orchestration:\n\n| Phase | Workflow name | Purpose |\n|-------|--------------|---------|\n| 1 | `list-tasks` | Discover available work. Output is JSONL (one task per line). |\n| 2 | `main` | Do the work. Receives a task ID via `CLOCHE_TASK_ID` env var. |\n| 3 | `finalize` | Post-main cleanup. Runs on **both**