{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01Q5zEFDKFsiuMCqoJmTFwWB","type":"tool_result","content":"   378→\n   379→## Setting Up Host Workflows\n   380→\n   381→The `host.cloche` file is the orchestration layer that ties everything together.\n   382→When you run `cloche init`, a minimal `host.cloche` with just a `main` workflow is\n   383→generated. As your project grows, you can add `list-tasks` and `finalize` workflows\n   384→to automate task discovery and cleanup.\n   385→\n   386→The daemon recognizes three workflow names in `host.cloche` and runs them in order:\n   387→\n   388→1. **`list-tasks`** — discover available work\n   389→2. **`main`** — execute the work\n   390→3. **`finalize`** — clean up after the work completes\n   391→\n   392→A fourth optional workflow, **`release-task`**, can be defined for releasing stale\n   393→claimed tasks back to open status. It is not part of the automatic loop — it runs on\n   394→demand when triggered from the web dashboard's Release button.\n   395→\n   396→All these workflows live in the same `.cloche/host.cloche` file. Only `main` is\n   397→required; `list-tasks`, `finalize`, and `release-task` are optional.\n   398→\n   399→### `list-tasks` — Discovering Work\n   400→\n   401→The `list-tasks` workflow runs first. Its job is to query your task tracker (issue\n   402→tracker, project board, ticket queue, etc.) and output a list of available tasks.\n   403→\n   404→**When it runs:** The daemon calls `list-tasks` at the start of each orchestration\n   405→loop iteration, before launching any new `main` runs.\n   406→\n   407→**Output format:** The final step must write JSONL (one JSON object per line) to\n   408→`$CLOCHE_STEP_OUTPUT`. Each line represents a task:\n   409→\n   410→```json\n   411→{\"id\": \"PROJ-42\", \"status\": \"open\", \"title\": \"Fix login bug\", \"description\": \"Users report...\"}\n   412→{\"id\": \"PROJ-43\", \"status\": \"in-progress\", \"title\": \"Add caching\", \"description\": \"...\"}\n   413→{\"id\": \"PROJ-44\", \"status\": \"open\", \"title\": \"Update docs\", \"description\": \"...\"}\n   414→```\n   415→\n   416→The daemon picks the first task with `status: \"open\"` and passes it to `main`.\n   417→Tasks that were recently assigned are deduplicated within a timeout window (default\n   418→5 minutes) to prevent the same task from being picked repeatedly.\n   419→\n   420→**How to configure:** Write a script that queries your task source and outputs JSONL:\n   421→\n   422→```\n   423→workflow \"list-tasks\" {\n   424→  step fetch-tickets {\n   425→    run     = \"bash .cloche/scripts/ready-tasks.sh\"\n   426→    results = [success, fail]\n   427→  }"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"0a1eb545-c5fc-4d99-8df4-f479f783e58f","uuid":"e012d06a-80cd-4864-92de-f4fe00d57f3b","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/workspace/docs/USAGE.md","content":"\n## Setting Up Host Workflows\n\nThe `host.cloche` file is the orchestration layer that ties everything together.\nWhen you run `cloche init`, a minimal `host.cloche` with just a `main` workflow is\ngenerated. As your project grows, you can add `list-tasks` and `finalize` workflows\nto automate task discovery and cleanup.\n\nThe daemon recognizes three workflow names in `host.cloche` and runs them in order:\n\n1. **`list-tasks`** — discover available work\n2. **`main`** — execute the work\n3. **`finalize`** — clean up after the work completes\n\nA fourth optional workflow, **`release-task`**, can be defined for releasing stale\nclaimed tasks back to open status. It is not part of the automatic loop — it runs on\ndemand when triggered from the web dashboard's Release button.\n\nAll these workflows live in the same `.cloche/host.cloche` file. Only `main` is\nrequired; `list-tasks`, `finalize`, and `release-task` are optional.\n\n### `list-tasks` — Discovering Work\n\nThe `list-tasks` workflow runs first. Its job is to query your task tracker (issue\ntracker, project board, ticket queue, etc.) and output a list of available tasks.\n\n**When it runs:** The daemon calls `list-tasks` at the start of each orchestration\nloop iteration, before launching any new `main` runs.\n\n**Output format:** The final step must write JSONL (one JSON object per line) to\n`$CLOCHE_STEP_OUTPUT`. Each line represents a task:\n\n```json\n{\"id\": \"PROJ-42\", \"status\": \"open\", \"title\": \"Fix login bug\", \"description\": \"Users report...\"}\n{\"id\": \"PROJ-43\", \"status\": \"in-progress\", \"title\": \"Add caching\", \"description\": \"...\"}\n{\"id\": \"PROJ-44\", \"status\": \"open\", \"title\": \"Update docs\", \"description\": \"...\"}\n```\n\nThe daemon picks the first task with `status: \"open\"` and passes it to `main`.\nTasks that were recently assigned are deduplicated within a timeout window (default\n5 minutes) to prevent the same task from being picked repeatedly.\n\n**How to configure:** Write a script that queries your task source and outputs JSONL:\n\n```\nworkflow \"list-tasks\" {\n  step fetch-tickets {\n    run     = \"bash .cloche/scripts/ready-tasks.sh\"\n    results = [success, fail]\n  }","numLines":50,"startLine":378,"totalLines":920}}}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_014rcvcjPHAiwCJg4gAjiaqu","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_017ytbAGKUZSmQ4hpBeNsV4F","name":"Read","input":{"file_path":"/workspace/docs/USAGE.md","offset":500,"limit":55},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1872,"cache_read_input_tokens":65657,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1872},"output_tokens":25,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"0a1eb545-c5fc-4d99-8df4-f479f783e58f","uuid":"dde9d40e-46d9-4df2-8242-2bf3fa0bb3cc"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_017ytbAGKUZSmQ4hpBeNsV4F","type":"tool_result","content":"   500→  }\n   501→\n   502→  close-task:success -> done\n   503→  close-task:fail    -> done\n   504→}\n   505→```\n   506→\n   507→A typical `finalize` script checks `$CLOCHE_MAIN_OUTCOME` and acts accordingly —\n   508→closing the ticket on success, or posting a failure comment for investigation.\n   509→Wiring both results to `done` (not `abort`) ensures the daemon treats the\n   510→finalize phase as complete regardless of the cleanup script's exit status.\n   511→\n   512→**If omitted:** The daemon skips the finalize phase entirely. This is fine if you\n   513→don't need automated cleanup.\n   514→\n   515→### `release-task` — Releasing Stale Claims\n   516→\n   517→The `release-task` workflow handles releasing tasks that are stuck in `in_progress`\n   518→status without an active worker. This happens when a run fails, the daemon restarts,\n   519→or a container is lost. The web dashboard detects these stale tasks and shows a\n   520→**Release** button next to them.\n   521→\n   522→**When it runs:** On demand, when a user clicks Release in the web dashboard. The\n   523→daemon sets `CLOCHE_TASK_ID` to the task being released.\n   524→\n   525→**How to configure:**\n   526→\n   527→```\n   528→workflow \"release-task\" {\n   529→  step release-task {\n   530→    run     = \"bash .cloche/scripts/release-task.sh\"\n   531→    results = [success, fail]\n   532→  }\n   533→\n   534→  release-task:success -> done\n   535→  release-task:fail    -> abort\n   536→}\n   537→```\n   538→\n   539→A typical release script returns the ticket to `open` status and unassigns the owner\n   540→in your task tracker.\n   541→\n   542→**If omitted:** The Release button will not function. Stale tasks must be manually\n   543→unclaimed in your task tracker.\n   544→\n   545→### Putting It All Together\n   546→\n   547→The three-phase model enables fully automated task pipelines:\n   548→\n   549→1. The orchestration loop calls `list-tasks` to find open work\n   550→2. It picks an open task and launches `main` with the task context\n   551→3. `main` prepares a prompt, dispatches a container workflow, and optionally merges results\n   552→4. `finalize` closes the ticket or reports failure\n   553→5. The loop repeats, picking the next open task\n   554→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"0a1eb545-c5fc-4d99-8df4-f479f783e58f","uuid":"38773c18-c071-4c06-9314-03a191f5e826","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/workspace/docs/USAGE.md","content":"  }\n\n  close-task:success -> done\n  close-task:fail    -> done\n}\n```\n\nA typical `finalize` script checks `$CLOCHE_MAIN_OUTCOME` and acts accordingly —\nclosing the ticket on success, or posting a failure comment for investigation.\nWiring both results to `done` (not `abort`) ensures the daemon treats the\nfinalize phase as complete regardless of the cleanup script's exit status.\n\n**If omitted:** The daemon skips the finalize phase entirely. This is fine if you\ndon't need automated cleanup.\n\n### `release-task` — Releasing Stale Claims\n\nThe `release-task` workflow handles releasing tasks that are stuck in `in_progress`\nstatus without an active worker. This happens when a run fails, the daemon restarts,\nor a container is lost. The web dashboard detects these stale tasks and shows a\n**Release** button next to them.\n\n**When it runs:** On demand, when a user clicks Release in the web dashboard. The\ndaemon sets `CLOCHE_TASK_ID` to the task being released.\n\n**How to configure:**\n\n```\nworkflow \"release-task\" {\n  step release-task {\n    run     = \"bash .cloche/scripts/release-task.sh\"\n    results = [success, fail]\n  }\n\n  release-task:success -> done\n  release-task:fail    -> abort\n}\n```\n\nA typical release script returns the ticket to `open` status and unassigns the owner\nin your task tracker.\n\n**If omitted:** The Release button will not function. Stale tasks must be manually\nunclaimed in your task tracker.\n\n### Putting It All Together\n\nThe three-phase model enables fully automated task pipelines:\n\n1. The orchestration loop calls `list-tasks` to find open work\n2. It picks an open task and launches `main` with the task context\n3. `main` prepares a prompt, dispatches a container workflow, and optionally merges results\n4. `finalize` closes the ticket or reports failure\n5. The loop repeats, picking the next open task\n","numLines":55,"startLine":500,"totalLines":920}}}
